# rcc-v2 Mission

rcc-v2 (Rosey CloudCannon Connector) is a client-side plugin that enables visual editing of [Rosey](https://rosey.app/) translation files inside CloudCannon's Visual Editor. It bridges Rosey's `data-rosey` translation keys and CloudCannon's live editing JS API, letting editors switch between locales and edit translations directly on the page.

## How It Works (MVP — DOM swap approach)

1. Loads only inside the Visual Editor (gated on `window.inEditorMode` / `cloudcannon:load` event)
2. Acquires the CloudCannon JS API handle via `CloudCannonAPI.useVersion("v1", true)`
3. Discovers available locales by fetching the build-time manifest at `/_rcc/locales.json` (generated by `write-locales --dest`)
4. Finds the snapshot boundary: first `[data-rcc]`, then `<main>` — no attribute required for standard layouts
5. Filters out any locales listed in `data-rcc-exclude` on the boundary element
6. Injects a collapsible, draggable locale switcher FAB (floating action button) with a popover menu
7. On locale switch:
   - Tears down any existing translation view (swaps the original container back in)
   - Clones the snapshot boundary container and strips all CC editing infrastructure from the clone (custom elements, `data-editable`, `data-prop` attributes)
   - Swaps the original out of the DOM and the clean clone in — CC's MutationObserver auto-dehydrates all editables on the removed original, and creates nothing on the inert clone
   - Tracks `[data-rosey]` elements in the clone, resolves their Rosey keys
   - For each: fetches the translation value via `file.data.get()`, sets `innerHTML`, creates an inline editor via `api.createTextEditableRegion()` with stale-closure guards, pushes user edits back with `file.data.set()`
   - Listens for external `change` events on the dataset to keep editors in sync
8. On "Original" switch: swaps the original container back in — CC's MutationObserver auto-reconnects all editables, restoring normal editing
9. Rosey keys are built by walking up DOM collecting `data-rosey-ns` segments, stopping at `data-rosey-root`, joined with `:`

## Editable Regions Independence

The RCC does **not** require editable regions, Bookshop, or any existing inline editing infrastructure. It creates its own ProseMirror editors via `createTextEditableRegion()` on every `data-rosey` element — sites with no `data-editable`, no `data-prop`, and no Bookshop still get full visual translation editing in locale view. The Bookshop Compatibility and DOM Swap sections below describe how the RCC *handles* sites that do have editing infrastructure — these are compatibility features, not prerequisites. That said, the experience is best when paired with editable regions: the "Original" view gets full inline editing of source text, and the input config prescan can inherit toolbar settings from existing editors.

## Key API Surface

`window.CloudCannonAPI.useVersion("v1", true)` after `cloudcannon:load`:

| API | Purpose |
|-----|---------|
| `api.dataset("locales_fr")` | Get a dataset object for a locale file |
| `dataset.items()` | Get the file handle(s) within a dataset |
| `file.data.get({ slug })` | Read a value from the locale file |
| `file.data.set({ slug, value })` | Push edits back to the data file |
| `dataset.addEventListener("change", ...)` | Listen for external data changes |
| `api.createTextEditableRegion(el, onChange, opts)` | Create an inline ProseMirror editor on an existing element |

## DOM Swap Mechanism

When the user picks a locale, the entire snapshot boundary container (`[data-rcc]` or `<main>`) is replaced with a clean clone. The clone has no CC custom elements, no `data-editable`, no `data-prop` — it is completely inert from CC's perspective. CC's document-level MutationObserver handles all cleanup automatically:

- **Swap out**: `original.replaceWith(clone)` removes the original. CC calls `dehydrateDataEditableRegions()` on the removed subtree, disconnecting all editables and listeners.
- **Clone is inert**: No `data-editable` or custom elements means CC creates nothing on it. Zero listeners, zero interference with our `createTextEditableRegion` calls.
- **Swap back**: `clone.replaceWith(original)` re-inserts the original. CC calls `hydrateDataEditableRegions()`, reconnecting existing editables. Normal editing fully restored.

The clone is processed while detached from the DOM, so there are no MutationObserver callbacks, no `connectedCallback` firings, and no race conditions during cleanup.

## Bookshop Compatibility

Sites using [Bookshop](https://github.com/CloudCannon/bookshop) for component-based live editing need additional sanitization. Bookshop's runtime uses `<!--bookshop-live name(...) params(...) -->` HTML comments as component markers and a global `window.bookshopLive` singleton that XPath-scans the entire document for these comments on every `cloudcannon:update` event, re-rendering component HTML between them.

The RCC handles this with two layers:

1. **Comment stripping**: `cleanClone()` removes all `<!--bookshop-live-->` comments from the clone via a `TreeWalker`. With no comment markers in the document, Bookshop's XPath scan finds nothing and produces zero component updates.
2. **`data-cms-bind` stripping**: `stripCCAttributes()` also removes `data-cms-bind` (Bookshop's click-to-edit panel binding attribute) from clone elements.
3. **Update cycle pausing**: `switchLocale()` monkey-patches `window.bookshopLive.update` to a no-op during locale view, preventing unnecessary XPath scans. `teardownEditors()` restores the original method before swapping the original container back in.

On restore, the original container (with real Bookshop comments) returns to the DOM. `teardownEditors()` then strips all `data-cms-bind` attributes from the original and forces a Bookshop re-render via `forceBookshopRerender()`. Stripping `data-cms-bind` is necessary because Bookshop's `graftTrees` preserves element nodes when only text content changed — and CC's overlay system tracks elements by reference, refusing to recreate overlays for re-inserted elements it already "knows." With `data-cms-bind` stripped, the next Bookshop render sees a shallow-clone mismatch in `graftTrees`, replaces the element with a fresh virtual DOM node, and `refreshInterface()` creates overlays on the new node. Bookshop's `cloudcannon:update` listener resumes finding comments and re-rendering normally.

## Stale Translation Detection

Locale entries store three fields: `original` (the source text when the translation was last acknowledged), `value` (the translation), and `_base_original` (the current source text from `base.json`, updated by `write-locales` on every run). When `original !== _base_original`, the translation is flagged as stale.

In the Visual Editor:
- Stale elements get an amber dashed border and a faint amber background
- The FAB shows an amber count badge with the number of stale translations
- Each locale button in the popover has a toggle row (chevron + count) that opens a separate floating stale panel beside the popover, listing stale items with per-item "Mark as reviewed" (checkmark) buttons and a "Resolve all" button
- Staleness is resolved by editing the translation (auto-resolves), clicking a per-item resolve button, or clicking "Resolve all"
- All paths update the locale's `original` via `file.data.set({ slug: "key.original", value: baseOriginal })`

At build time:
- `write-locales` always sets `_base_original` to the current `base.json` original for every entry (new and existing)
- `write-locales` never modifies `original` or `value` on existing entries — only the editor does

## Known Constraints

- **Locale values must be HTML**: Rosey originals are always HTML (the SSG has already converted Markdown to HTML at build time). Locale `.value` fields must also be HTML because Rosey substitutes them directly into the built HTML output. To ensure this, rcc-v2 overrides `inputConfig.type` to `"html"` for all editors, even when the original field is configured as `type: markdown`. This forces ProseMirror to serialize `onChange` output as HTML rather than raw Markdown — avoiding the need to bundle a Markdown parser and eliminating parser-mismatch risk with the user's SSG.
- **ProseMirror editors cannot be destroyed**: `createTextEditableRegion` returns `{ setContent }` but no `destroy()`. Old ProseMirror instances stay alive after teardown and fire `onChange` when the DOM changes underneath them. A `switchGeneration` counter makes stale closures no-ops.
- **ProseMirror onChange fires on init**: `createTextEditableRegion` normalises content and fires `onChange` immediately. A `setupComplete` flag blocks these writes until all editors are created.
- **`createTextEditableRegion` does not use existing innerHTML**: The editor starts empty; you must call `editor.setContent(value)` after creation to populate it (matching CC's own `EditableText.mountEditor()` pattern).
- **Slug path separator**: CloudCannon's data API uses `.` as a path separator. Colons in Rosey keys are literal characters. To target the `value` field inside a `{ original, value }` locale entry, use slug `roseyKey.value`.
- **Skip `setContent` on focused editors**: When a data `change` event fires, `setContent` must be skipped for any editor the user is actively typing in — otherwise ProseMirror resets the cursor and steals focus. This matches CC's own `EditableText.shouldUpdate()` pattern which checks `!this.focused`.
- **Console logging**: Verbose logging (gated on `data-rcc-verbose`) uses summary counts rather than per-element lines to keep the console readable. The dataset change listener logs one summary line per event, not one per tracked element.
- **`<editable-text>` replacement tag**: When stripping CC custom elements from the clone, `<editable-text>` is replaced with `<span>` (inline) by default, but upgrades to `<div>` if `data-type="block"|"text"` is set or the element contains block-level children. This prevents invalid HTML nesting.
- **Input config resolution**: The `inputConfig` passed to `createTextEditableRegion` is resolved in priority order: (1) prescanned config from CC editable regions, (2) CC's internal defaults with `type: "html"`. The prescan dispatches `cloudcannon-api` `get-input-config` events on each `[data-rosey]` element that has `data-prop` + `data-editable="text"` / `<editable-text>` in the original container at init time. This captures the exact `inputConfig` CC uses for each field — including expanded toolbar options CC computes from `_inputs` defaults. A 200ms timeout guards against missing event handlers. Before passing any config to `createTextEditableRegion`, the `type` is overridden to `"html"` (see "Locale values must be HTML" constraint above) while preserving all other options.
- **Element type inference**: When `data-type` is not set on an element (typical for non-editable-region sites), the injector auto-detects inline vs block using `inferElementType()`: elements containing block-level children (checked via `BLOCK_LEVEL_SELECTOR`) get `elementType: "block"`, everything else gets `"span"`. Inference runs at **tracking time** (in `trackElements()`) when the clone element still has its original SSG source HTML, and the result is stored on `TrackedElement.inferredType`. This prevents a degradation loop where a translation that has lost block-level tags would cause the editor to downgrade to `"span"`, making it impossible to re-add block content.
- **Locale discovery and manifest format**: The injector fetches `/_rcc/locales.json` (a build-time manifest generated by `write-locales --dest`). The manifest is a JSON object: `{ locales: ["fr","de"] }`. The `--dest` flag is required. No HTML attributes are needed for locale discovery. The `rosey build` command must include `--exclusions "\.(html?)$"` so that JSON files (including this manifest) are copied through as assets instead of being excluded by Rosey's default `\.(html?|json)$` regex.
- **Snapshot boundary**: The injector finds the boundary via `[data-rcc]` first, then `<main>`. To include nav/footer in locale switching, add `data-rcc` to a wrapper element that encompasses all translatable content. `<body>` cannot be used as the boundary because it hosts the RCC's own UI (FAB, popover, stale panel), CloudCannon's editing infrastructure, and `<script>` tags — swapping it would destroy all of those.
- **Per-page locale exclusion**: `data-rcc-exclude="de"` on the boundary element filters locales from the FAB for that page only. Comma-separated for multiple codes.
- **Elements without locale entries**: When a `[data-rosey]` element has no corresponding entry in the locale file (e.g. a component or array item added after the last `write-locales` run), the element is still shown in the locale view for layout integrity but rendered at 45% opacity with `pointer-events: none`. No inline editor is created, no stale detection runs, and no `onChange` writes can occur. A `write-locales` run is required to make the element translatable.
- **`data-cms-bind` overlays require fresh elements**: CC's overlay system tracks `data-cms-bind` elements by DOM reference. Re-inserting the same element objects after a swap doesn't trigger overlay recreation, even with `refreshInterface()`. The fix is to strip `data-cms-bind` from the original after swap, then force a Bookshop re-render. Bookshop's `graftTrees` sees a shallow-clone mismatch (virtual DOM has the attribute, real DOM doesn't), replaces the element with a fresh node, and `refreshInterface()` creates overlays on it.
- **`dataset.items()` hangs for missing files**: When `data_config` points to a file CC cannot find, `dataset.items()` returns a promise that **never settles** (no rejection, no null). The injector guards against this with a 5-second timeout. The most common cause is a `source` setting in `cloudcannon.config.yml` — `data_config` paths are resolved relative to `source`, so if `source: src` and the rosey directory is at the project root, the paths won't resolve. CC does not support `../` in config paths, so the fix is to remove the `source` key entirely and prepend its value to all affected paths (`collections_config.*.path`, `data_config.*.path`, `paths.*`, `file_config.*.glob`). The `init` CLI auto-detects `source` and performs this rewrite automatically.

## Hybrid Translation (Split-by-Directory + Rosey)

For pages with large body content (blog posts, documentation), a hybrid approach is recommended: body content is translated via per-locale content collections (split-by-directory), while shared UI strings (nav, footer, breadcrumbs, sidebar headings) continue using Rosey. The SSG builds locale pages natively, and Rosey merges with them in postbuild -- it respects existing content and only translates `data-rosey` elements. The RCC works identically on both pure-Rosey pages and hybrid pages; no changes to the injector are needed.

## CLI Tooling

- **`write-locales`**: Node CLI that reads Rosey's `base.json` and creates/updates locale JSON files + the `_rcc/locales.json` manifest. When `--locales` is not passed, auto-detects locales from existing files in `rosey/locales/`, filtering out `*.urls.json` (native Rosey URL translation files). Also reads `cloudcannon.config.yml` to validate that `data_config` entries exist for each locale. The `--keep-unused` flag preserves locale keys not present in `base.json` (useful during v1→v2 migration to remap translations before cleanup). See codebase map for details.
- **`init`**: Setup wizard that configures the entire Rosey + RCC stack (deps, postbuild, CC config). Supports both interactive mode (prompts for all options) and headless mode (`--yes --locales fr,de`) for agent/CI automation. In headless mode, `--locales` is the only required flag; everything else has sensible defaults.

For deep reference on how CloudCannon's editable regions work internally, see `.cursor/docs/editable-regions-*.md`.
